[4] Suspected, monitored, prevention, research

20 Apr 2015 Guinea: Opposition protests slow down anti-Ebola war in Guinea
http://www.punchng.com/news/opposition-protests-slow-down-anti-ebola-war-in-guinea/
[According to officials, the protests made it difficult to continue Ebola monitoring efforts, and about 100 people who were under surveillance in Conakry managed to escape.]

21 Apr 2015: Guinea: Prosecutor demands death penalty over Ebola murders
http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/guinea-prosecutor-demands-death-penalty-over-ebola-murders-756731
[Guinean prosecutor William Fernandez seeks the death penalty for the 15 arrested individuals who are charged with killing the 9-member team of Ebola educators, journalists and public officials. Locals attacked the group during an outreach visit to the city of Womey. Eight bodies were found in a septic tank of a nearby elementary school 2 days after the attack. The charges are murder, criminal conspiracy, robbery, assault and theft. A total of 26 residents were accused of the charges. However, Fernandez seeks the death penalty for 15 of them and acquittal of the rest.]

21 Apr 2015: Guinea: Fresh electoral protests threaten to undermine Ebola response
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504210370.html?viewall=1
[At least 3 people were killed last week, and more than 50 people wounded, during 2 days of violent political protests in Guinea's capital, Conakry. New protests are scheduled for today, 21 Apr 2015, in the capital over the deaths of at least 3 people during last week's protests. The protests are not related to the Ebola outbreak, but they have already severely interfered with the Ebola response.]

22 Apr 2015 Guinea: 11 get life sentences over Guinea Ebola worker murder
http://www.voanews.com/content/eleven-handed-life-sentences-over-guinea-ebola-worker-murder/2730209.html
[Out of 26 defendants, the prosecutor recommended the death penalty for 11 and acquittal for the rest. The victims include local administrators, medical officers and journalists. The bodies of 8 victims were found in latrines, in the village of Womey.]

22 Apr 2015 Liberia: Destruction angers Ellen [Sirleaf]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504220738.html
[Returning from a policy visit to the US, President Sirleaf expressed frustration with the continuing destruction in Liberia, saying it undermines efforts to gain support from foreign governors and partners. The outbreak of destruction started last Thu 16 Apr 2015 as a result of a violent protest by commercial motorcyclists in which police stations were burned down.]

21 Apr 2015: Sierra Leone's mining industry moving on from Ebola
http://www.proactiveinvestors.co.uk/companies/news/79513/sierra-leones-mining-industry-moving-on-from-ebola--79513.html
[Approval has been issued for Sierra Rutile to open a new USD 77 million mine in Sierra Leone.]

21 Apr 2015 Sierra Leone: Ebola retreat brings cheer to Sierra Leone chimps
http://phys.org/news/2015-04-sierra-leone-chimpanzees-home-ebola.html
[Funded by tourism, the facility was forced to close in August 2014 because of the Ebola virus outbreak. It has now reopened, and tourists have returned.]

20 Apr 2015: Sierra Leone: Stray dog population doubles during Ebola crisis
http://www.voanews.com/content/sierra-leone-stray-dog-population-ebola-crisis-/2727392.html
[During the outbreak, many residents feared their dogs could infect them with the Ebola virus, and abandoned their dogs. Rabies vaccines were not available, as well, until recently, raising the possibility of increased numbers of rabies infections amongst the nearly doubled stray dog population currently present. Rabies is endemic in Sierra Leone. According to the US Centers for Disease Control, dogs may carry the virus, but they cannot transmit it.]

21 Apr 2015 Sierra Leone: Street Child sends 1000 Ebola orphans to school
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504220989.html?viewall=1

22 Apr 2015: Sierra Leone hunts Ebola quarantine escapees
http://medicalxpress.com/news/2015-04-sierra-leone-ebola-quarantine-escapees.html
[Sierra Leone's police are searching for 7 people who fled a slum which was under quarantine after a family member died of Ebola virus disease. The quarantine was for the densely populated Moa Wharf township. The 7 people are from the same household and are believed to have gone into hiding in Goderich fishing community, around 30 km (20 miles) west of Freetown. Another 6 people who had been in contact with the deceased were transferred to a clinic for observation. This is where the challenge to elimination of the virus from the population lies, that is, need for full compliance of the people. - Mod.LK]

22 Apr 2015 UK: A scare about a potential Ebola case caused part of a hospital to be closed
http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/news/health/local-health/ebola-scare-causes-hospital-to-briefly-shut-1-6702044
[The minor injuries unit at Bognor's War Memorial Hospital was closed for 2 hours when a patient was seen with a potentially infectious disease. The unit was reopened on the advice of Public Health England. No testing was performed]

21 Apr 2015 USA (New York): Public Health response to an imported case of Ebola virus disease--New York City, 2014
http://www.cdc.gov/media/pdf/dpk/2015/dpk-eis/public-health-response-to-an-imported-case-of-ebola-virus-disease-new-york-city-2014.pdf

20 Apr 2015 USA (Texas): Judge halts worker's comp claim for Ebola nurse Nina Pham
http://www.ktre.com/story/28851182/judge-halts-workers-comp-claim-for-ebola-nurse-nina-pham

20 Apr 2015: Zimbabwe: Government bans dead bodies from Ebola hit countries
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504200585.html?viewall=1

Region
------
20 Apr 2015 Africa: Ebola--tackling the epidemic across country borders
http://allafrica.com/stories/201504201379.html?viewall=1

20 Apr 2015 West Africa: Ebola lying in wait
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/21/health/ebola-lying-in-wait.html?_r=0
[Studies hint of possible Ebola antibodies in human blood samples drawn in West Africa long before the current outbreak. Genetic analysis suggests the West African virus split from a parent strain in Central Africa at least 10 years ago and perhaps as long as 150 years ago. Scientists have found signs in human blood that suggest immune reactions to Ebola in 14 other countries: 12 in Africa, as well as Panama and the Philippines.]

22 Apr 2015 West Africa: Ebola survivors donate plasma to tackle outbreak
http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2015-04/uol-esd042215.php
[The 1st donations of plasma from survivors of the Ebola epidemic in Sierra Leone have been received by an international research team working to help treat current and future disease outbreaks in West Africa.]

