Research, vaccines, drugs
-------------------------
20 Apr 2015: Apes lack Ebola protection, scientists warn
http://www.scidev.net/global/disease/news/apes-lack-ebola-protection-scientists-warn.html

21 Apr 2015: Scientists to share real-time genetic data on deadly MERS, Ebola
http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/04/21/health-viruses-genetics-idUSL5N0XE48420150421?rpc=401
[The aim of the project is to speed search for treatments and vaccines. The MERS gene sequences are already available for MERS cases, and Ebola sequences will soon be available for Ebola cases on Virological.org. The global health charity Wellcome Trust is funding the project, which will allow data access by anyone in real time. - Mod.LK]

21 Apr 2015: Ebola Transmission linked to a single traditional funeral ceremony -- Kissidougou, Guinea, December 2014-January 2015
http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6414a4.htm?s_cid=mm6414a4_e
[Centers for Diseases Control and Prevention, Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report]

22 Apr 2015: Researchers develop Ebola treatment effective 3 days
http://medicalxpress.com/news/2015-04-ebola-treatment-effective-days-infection.html
[Named TKM Ebola, the treatment uses a sequence-specific short strand of RNA (siRNA), designed to target and interfere with the Ebola virus, leaving it noninfective. It is the 1st to be shown effective against the new Makona outbreak strain of Ebola in animals infected with the virus that showed symptoms of the disease. Researchers were able to protect all of the nonhuman primate subjects against a lethal Makona Ebola infection when treatment began 3 days following infection, when the infected showed clinical signs of disease and had detectable levels of virus in their blood. All of the test primates showed advanced symptoms, but those receiving treatment had milder symptoms and recovered fully. The untreated controls died from the disease on days 8 and 9, similar to that reported in the field after patients begin showing symptoms of Ebola. The treatment also protected against liver and kidney dysfunction and blood disorders that occur during an Ebola infection.]

22 Apr 2015: Study examines long-term adverse health effects of Ebola survivors
http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2015-04/tumh-sel042215.php
[After the 2007-2008 Bundibugyo Ebola virus disease outbreak in Uganda that killed 39 people, survivors experienced negative health effects for more than 2 years.]

